{"add":{"doc":{"id":"d22039e5a9ccd9a8463becfc7abb5487174e62b6a9cb2af1b8418489ba74fe7b","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/24/Ian_Thorpe_with_a_smile.jpg/220px-Ian_Thorpe_with_a_smile.jpg","previous":[],"after":["At the age of 14, he became the youngest male ever to represent Australia, and his victory in the 400 metre freestyle at the 1998 Perth World Championships made him the youngest ever individual male World Champion. After that victory, Thorpe dominated the 400 m freestyle, winning the event at every Olympic, World, Commonwealth and Pan Pacific Swimming Championships until his break after the 2004 Olympics. Aside from 13 individual long-course world records, Thorpe anchored the Australian relay teams, numbering the victories in the 4 × 100 m and the 4 × 200 m freestyle relays in Sydney, among his five relay world records. His wins in the 200 m and 400 m and his bronze in the 100 m freestyle in Athens have made him the only male to have won medals in the 100–200–400 combination."]}}}